# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pie-donut-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] In graph drawing, a **circular layout** is a style of drawing that places the vertices of a graph on a circle, often evenly spaced so that they form the vertices of a regular polygon.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Circular layouts are a good fit for communications network topologies such as star or ring networks, and for the cyclic parts of metabolic networks.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] For graphs with a known Hamiltonian cycle, a circular layout allows the cycle to be depicted as the circle, and in this way circular layouts form the basis of the LCF notation for Hamiltonian cubic graphs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] A circular layout may be used on its own for an entire graph drawing, but it also may be used as the layout for smaller clusters of vertices within a larger graph drawing, such as its biconnected components, clusters of genes in a gene interaction graph, or natural subgroups within a social network.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] If multiple vertex circles are used in this way, other methods such as force-directed graph drawing may be used to arrange the clusters.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] The edges of the drawing may be depicted as chords of the circle, as circular arcs (possibly perpendicular to the vertex circle, so that the edges model lines of the Poincaré disk model of hyperbolic geometry), or as other types of curve.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] The visual distinction between the inside and the outside of the vertex circle in a circular layout may be used to separate two different styles of edge drawing.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] For instance, a circular drawing algorithm of Gansner & Koren (2007) uses edge bundling within the circle, together with some edges that are not bundled, drawn outside the circle.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] For circular layouts of regular graphs, with edges drawn both inside and outside as circular arcs, the angle of incidence of one of these arcs with the vertex circle is the same at both ends of the arc, a property that simplifies the optimization of the angular resolution of the drawing.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Several authors have studied the problem of finding a permutation of the vertices of a circular layout that minimizes the number of edge crossings when all edges are drawn inside the vertex circle.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] This number of crossings is zero only for outerplanar graphs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] For other graphs, it may be optimized or reduced separately for each biconnected component of the graph before combining the solutions, as these components may be drawn so that they do not interact.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] In general, minimizing the number of crossings is NP-complete.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] (1995) described an approximation algorithm based on balanced cuts or edge separators, subsets of few edges whose removal disconnects the given graph into two subgraphs with approximately equal numbers of vertices.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] After finding an approximate cut, their algorithm arranges the two subgraphs on each side of the cut recursively, without considering the additional crossings formed by the edges that cross the cut.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Their work cites a paper by Fan Chung and Shing-Tung Yau from 1994 that claimed $\rho =O(1)$ , but this was later found to have an erroneous proof.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Instead, the best approximation known for the balanced cut problem has $\rho =O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ , giving this circular layout algorithm an approximation ratio of $O(\log ^{3}n)$ on graphs that have a large number of crossings relative to their vertex degrees.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Heuristic methods for reducing the crossing complexity have also been devised, based e.g. on a careful vertex insertion order and on local optimization.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] A circular layout may also be used to maximize the number of crossings.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] In particular, choosing a random permutation for the vertices causes each possible crossing to occur with probability 1/3, so the expected number of crossings is within a factor of three of the maximum number of crossings among all possible layouts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/circular-layout] Derandomizing this method gives a deterministic approximation algorithm with approximation ratio three.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A **pie chart** (or a **circle chart**) is a circular statistical graphic which is divided into slices to illustrate numerical proportion.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] In a pie chart, the arc length of each slice (and consequently its central angle and area) is proportional to the quantity it represents.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] While it is named for its resemblance to a pie which has been sliced, there are variations on the way it can be presented.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The earliest known pie chart is generally credited to William Playfair's *Statistical Breviary* of 1801.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Pie charts are very widely used in the business world and the mass media.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] However, they have been criticized, and many experts recommend avoiding them, as research has shown it is more difficult to make simple comparisons such as the size of different sections of a given pie chart, or to compare data across different pie charts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Some research has shown pie charts perform well for comparing complex combinations of sections (e.g., "A + B vs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Commonly recommended alternatives to pie charts in most cases include bar charts, box plots, and dot plots.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The earliest known pie chart is generally credited to William Playfair's *Statistical Breviary* of 1801, in which two such graphs are used.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Playfair presented an illustration, which contained a series of pie charts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] One of those charts depicted the proportions of the Turkish Empire located in Asia, Europe and Africa before 1789.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] This invention was not widely used at first.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Playfair thought that pie charts were in need of a third dimension to add additional information.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Florence Nightingale may not have invented the pie chart, but she adapted it to make it more readable, which fostered its wide use, still today.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Nightingale reconfigured the pie chart making the length of the wedges variable instead of their width.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The graph, then, resembled a cock's comb.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] She was later assumed to have created it due to the obscurity and lack of practicality of Playfair's creation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The French engineer Charles Joseph Minard also used pie charts, in 1858.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A map of his from 1858 used pie charts to represent the cattle sent from all around France for consumption in Paris.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A 3D pie chart, or perspective pie chart, is used to give the chart a 3D look.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Often used for aesthetic reasons, the third dimension does not improve the reading of the data; on the contrary, these plots are difficult to interpret because of the distorted effect of perspective associated with the third dimension.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The use of superfluous dimensions not used to display the data of interest is discouraged for charts in general, not only for pie charts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A doughnut chart (also spelled donut) is a variant of the pie chart, with a blank center allowing for additional information about the data as a whole to be included.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Doughnut charts are similar to pie charts in that their aim is to illustrate proportions.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] This type of circular graph can support multiple statistics at once and it provides a better data intensity ratio than standard pie charts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] It does not have to contain information in the center.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A chart with one or more sectors separated from the rest of the disk is known as an *exploded pie chart*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] This effect is used to either highlight a sector, or to highlight smaller segments of the chart with small proportions.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The polar area diagram is similar to a usual pie chart, except sectors have equal angles and differ rather in how far each sector extends from the center of the circle.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] It is used to plot cyclic phenomena (e.g., counts of deaths by month).
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] For example, if the counts of deaths in each month for a year are to be plotted then there will be 12 sectors (one per month) all with the same angle of 30 degrees each.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The radius of each sector would be proportional to the square root of the death rate for the month, so the area of a sector represents the rate of deaths in a month.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] If the death rate in each month is subdivided by cause of death, it is possible to make multiple comparisons on one diagram, as is seen in the polar area diagram famously developed by Florence Nightingale.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The first known use of polar area diagrams was by André-Michel Guerry, which he called *courbes circulaires* (circular curves), in an 1829 paper showing seasonal and daily variation in wind direction over the year and births and deaths by hour of the day.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Léon Lalanne later used a polar diagram to show the frequency of wind directions around compass points in 1843.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The wind rose is still used by meteorologists.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Nightingale published her rose diagram in 1858.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Although the name "coxcomb" has come to be associated with this type of diagram, Nightingale originally used the term to refer to the publication in which this diagram first appeared—an attention-getting book of charts and tables—rather than to this specific type of diagram.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A ring chart, also known as a sunburst chart or a multilevel pie chart, is used to visualize hierarchical data, depicted by concentric circles.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The circle in the center represents the root node, with the hierarchy moving outward from the center.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A segment of the inner circle bears a hierarchical relationship to those segments of the outer circle which lie within the angular sweep of the parent segment.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A variant of the polar area chart is the spie chart, designed by Dror Feitelson.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The design superimposes a normal pie chart with a modified polar area chart to permit the comparison of two sets of related data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The base pie chart represents the first data set in the usual way, with different slice sizes.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The second set is represented by the superimposed polar area chart, using the same angles as the base, and adjusting the radii to fit the data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] For example, the base pie chart could show the distribution of age and gender groups in a population, and the overlay their representation among road casualties.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Age and gender groups that are especially susceptible to being involved in accidents then stand out as slices that extend beyond the original pie chart.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Square charts, also called waffle charts, are a form of pie charts that use squares instead of circles to represent percentages.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Similar to basic circular pie charts, square pie charts take each percentage out of a total 100%.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] They are often 10 by 10 grids, where each cell represents 1%.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Despite the name, circles, pictograms (such as of people), and other shapes may be used instead of squares.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] One major benefit to square charts is that smaller percentages, difficult to see on traditional pie charts, can be easily depicted.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The following example chart is based on preliminary results of the election for the European Parliament in 2004.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The table lists the number of seats allocated to each party group, along with the derived percentage of the total that they each make up.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The values in the last column, the derived central angle of each sector, is found by taking that percentage of 360.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] The size of each central angle is proportional to the size of the corresponding quantity, here the number of seats.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Since the sum of the central angles has to be 360°, the central angle for a quantity that is a fraction *Q* of the total is 360*Q* degrees.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] In the example, the central angle for the largest group (European People's Party (EPP)) is 135.7° because 0.377 times 360, rounded to one decimal place, equals 135.7.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] A flaw exhibited by pie charts is that they cannot show more than a few values without separating the visual encoding (the “slices”) from the data they represent (typically percentages).
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] When slices become too small, pie charts have to rely on colors, textures or arrows so the reader can understand them.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] This makes them unsuitable for use with larger amounts of data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Pie charts also take up a larger amount of space on the page compared to the more flexible bar charts, which do not need to have separate legends, and can display other values such as averages or targets at the same time.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Statisticians generally regard pie charts as a poor method of displaying information, and they are uncommon in scientific literature.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] One reason is that it is more difficult for comparisons to be made between the size of items in a chart when area is used instead of length and when different items are shown as different shapes.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Further, in research performed at AT&T Bell Laboratories, it was shown that comparison by angle was less accurate than comparison by length.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Most subjects have difficulty ordering the slices in the pie chart by size; when an equivalent bar chart is used the comparison is much easier.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Similarly, comparisons between data sets are easier using the bar chart.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] However, if the goal is to compare a given category (a slice of the pie) with the total (the whole pie) in a single chart and the multiple is close to 25 or 50 percent, then a pie chart can often be more effective than a bar graph.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] In a pie chart with many sections, several values may be represented with the same or similar colors, making interpretation difficult.
[src:pie-donut-charts/donut-chart] Several studies presented at the European Visualization Conference analyzed the relative accuracy of several pie chart formats, reaching the conclusion that pie charts and doughnut charts produce similar error levels when reading them, and square pie charts provide the most accurate reading.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:pie-donut-charts/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In mathematics, the **polar coordinate system** specifies a given point in a plane by using a distance and an angle as its two coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The distance from the pole is called the *radial coordinate*, *radial distance* or simply *radius*, and the angle is called the *angular coordinate*, *polar angle*, or *azimuth*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The pole is analogous to the origin in a Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are most appropriate in any context where the phenomenon being considered is inherently tied to direction and length from a center point in a plane, such as spirals.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Planar physical systems with bodies moving around a central point, or phenomena originating from a central point, are often simpler and more intuitive to model using polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar coordinate system is extended to three dimensions in two ways: the cylindrical coordinate system adds a second distance coordinate, and the spherical coordinate system adds a second angular coordinate.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Grégoire de Saint-Vincent and Bonaventura Cavalieri independently introduced the system's concepts in the mid-17th century, though the actual term *polar coordinates* has been attributed to Gregorio Fontana in the 18th century.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The initial motivation for introducing the polar system was the study of circular and orbital motion.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The concepts of angle and radius were already used by ancient peoples of the first millennium BC.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Greek astronomer Hipparchus (190–120 BC) created a table of chord functions giving the length of the chord for each angle, and there are references to his using polar coordinates in establishing stellar positions.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In *On Spirals*, Greek mathematician Archimedes describes his spiral, a function whose radius depends on the angle.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Greek work, however, did not extend to a full coordinate system.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] From the 8th century AD onward, astronomers developed methods for approximating and calculating the direction to Mecca (qibla)—and its distance—from any location on the Earth.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] From the 9th century onward they were using spherical trigonometry and map projection methods to determine these quantities accurately.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] There are various accounts of the introduction of polar coordinates as part of a formal coordinate system.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The full history of the subject is described in Harvard professor Julian Lowell Coolidge's *Origin of Polar Coordinates.* Mathematicians from Jesuit, Grégoire de Saint-Vincent, and Italian Bonaventura Cavalieri independently introduced the concepts in the mid-seventeenth century.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Saint-Vincent wrote about them privately in 1625 and published his work in 1647, while Cavalieri published his in 1635, with a corrected version appearing in 1653.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Cavalieri first used polar coordinates to solve a problem relating to the area within an Archimedean spiral.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] French mathematician Blaise Pascal subsequently used polar coordinates to calculate the length of parabolic arcs.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In *Method of Fluxions* (written 1671, published 1736), English mathematician Sir Isaac Newton examined the transformations between polar coordinates, which he referred to as the "Seventh Manner; For Spirals", and nine other coordinate systems.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] He is credited with originating the polar coordinate system in its analytic form and for originating bipolar coordinates in a strict sense.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the journal *Acta Eruditorum* (1691), Swiss mathematician Jacob Bernoulli used a system with a point on a line, called the *pole* and *polar axis* respectively.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Coordinates were specified by the distance from the pole and the angle from the *polar axis*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Bernoulli's work extended to the calculation of the radius of curvature of curves expressed in these coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term *polar coordinates* was attributed to Gregorio Fontana and used by 18th-century Italian writers.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term appeared in English in George Peacock's 1816 translation of Lacroix's *Differential and Integral Calculus*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Alexis Clairaut was the first to think of polar coordinates in three dimensions, and Leonhard Euler was the first to actually develop them.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The radial coordinate is often denoted by r or $\rho$ (rho).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angular coordinate is denoted by $\varphi$ (phi), specified by ISO standard 31-11 (now 80000-2:2019), or $\theta$ (theta) in mathematical literature oftentimes.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Angles in polar notation are generally expressed in either degrees or radians (2π rad being equal to 360°).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Degrees are traditionally used in navigation, surveying, and many applied disciplines, while radians are more common in mathematics and mathematical physics.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angle $\varphi$ is defined to start at 0° from a *reference direction*, and to increase for rotations in either clockwise (↻) or counterclockwise (↺) orientation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar angles decrease towards negative values for rotations in the respective opposite orientations.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Adding any number of full turns (360°) to the angular coordinate does not change the corresponding direction.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Similarly, any polar coordinate is identical to the coordinate with the negative radial component and the opposite direction (adding 180° to the polar angle).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Therefore, the same point $(r,\varphi )$ can be expressed with an infinite number of different polar coordinates $(r,\varphi +n\times 360^{\circ })$ and $(-r,\varphi +180^{\circ }+n\times 360^{\circ })=(-r,\varphi +(2n+1)\times 180^{\circ })$ , where n is an arbitrary integer.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Moreover, the pole itself can be expressed as $(0,\varphi )$ for any angle $\varphi$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Where a unique representation is needed for any point besides the pole, it is usual to limit r to positive numbers ( $r>0$ ) and $\varphi$ to either the interval $[0,360^{\circ })$ or the interval $(-180^{\circ },180^{\circ }]$ , which in radians are $[0,2\pi )$ or $(-\pi ,\pi ]$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Another convention, in reference to the usual codomain of the arctan function, is to allow for arbitrary nonzero real values of the radial component and restrict the polar angle to $(-90^{\circ },90^{\circ }]$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In all cases, a unique azimuth for the pole $r=0$ must be chosen, e.g., $\varphi =0$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A complex number consists of real numbers x and y , as well as an imaginary number $i^{2}=-1$ , which can be written as $z=x+iy$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Every complex number represents a point in the complex plane, thereby expressible by specifying either the point's Cartesian coordinates (called rectangular or Cartesian form) or the point's polar coordinates (called polar form).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In polar form, the distance r and angle coordinate $\varphi$ are often referred to as the number's magnitude of modulus and argument, respectively.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] To convert between the rectangular and polar forms of a complex number, the conversion formulae given above can be used.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For the operations of multiplication, division, exponentiation, and root extraction of complex numbers, it is generally much simpler to work with complex numbers expressed in polar form rather than rectangular form.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The equation defining a plane curve expressed in polar coordinates is known as a *polar equation*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In many cases, such an equation can simply be specified by defining *r* as a function of *φ*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The resulting curve then consists of points of the form (*r*(*φ*), *φ*) and can be regarded as the graph of the polar function *r*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Note that, in contrast to Cartesian coordinates, the independent variable *φ* is the *second* entry in the ordered pair.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Because of the circular nature of the polar coordinate system, many curves can be described by a rather simple polar equation, whereas their Cartesian form is much more intricate.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Among the best known of these curves are the polar rose, Archimedean spiral, lemniscate, limaçon, and cardioid.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For the circle, line, and polar rose below, it is understood that there are no restrictions on the domain and range of the curve.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This can be simplified in various ways, to conform to more specific cases, such as the equation $r(\varphi )=a$ for a circle with a center at the pole and radius *a*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the general case, the equation can be solved for *r*, giving $r=r_{0}\cos(\varphi -\gamma )+{\sqrt {a^{2}-r_{0}^{2}\sin ^{2}(\varphi -\gamma )}}$ The solution with a minus sign in front of the square root gives the same curve.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If $\epsilon >1$ , this equation defines a hyperbola; if $\epsilon =1$ , it defines a parabola; and if $\epsilon <1$ , it defines an ellipse.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The special case $\epsilon =0$ of the latter results in a circle of the radius $\ell$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Both are special cases of *r*(*φ*) = *a* cos(*kφ + γ*), with *γ* determining the phase and equivalently the rotation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *k* is an integer, these equations will produce a *k*-petaled rose if *k* is odd, or a 2*k*-petaled rose if *k* is even.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *k* is rational, but not an integer, a rose-like shape may form, but with overlapping petals.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Note that these equations never define a rose with 2, 6, 10, 14, etc. petals.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The variable *a* directly represents the length or amplitude of the petals of the rose, while *k* relates to their spatial frequency.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Archimedean spiral is a spiral discovered by Archimedes, which can also be expressed as a simple polar equation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] It is represented by the equation $r(\varphi )=a+b\varphi .$ Changing the parameter *a* will turn the spiral, while *b* controls the distance between the arms, which for a given spiral is always constant.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Archimedean spiral has two arms, one for *φ* > 0 and one for *φ* < 0.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The two arms are smoothly connected at the pole.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *a* = 0, taking the mirror image of one arm across the 90°/270° line will yield the other arm.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This curve is notable as one of the first curves, after the conic sections, to be described in a mathematical treatise, and as a prime example of a curve best defined by a polar equation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A quadratrix in the first quadrant $(x,y)$ is a curve with $y=\rho \sin \theta$ equal to the fraction of the quarter circle with radius r determined by the radius through the curve point.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] All the points $[g(\theta _{i}),\theta _{i}]$ where $\theta _{i}$ are solutions to the equation $f(\theta +2k\pi )=g(\theta )$ where k is an integer.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] All the points $[g(\theta _{i}),\theta _{i}]$ where $\theta _{i}$ are solutions to the equation $f(\theta +(2k+1)\pi )=-g(\theta )$ where k is an integer.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Calculus can be applied to equations expressed in polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angular coordinate *φ* is expressed in radians throughout this section, which is the conventional choice when doing calculus.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using *x* = *r* cos *φ* and *y* = *r* sin *φ*, one can derive a relationship between derivatives in Cartesian and polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using the inverse coordinates transformation, an analogous reciprocal relationship can be derived between the derivatives.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For other useful formulas including divergence, gradient, and Laplacian in polar coordinates, see curvilinear coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The arc length (length of a line segment) defined by a polar function is found by the integration over the curve *r*(*φ*).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let *L* denote this length along the curve starting from points *A* through to point *B*, where these points correspond to *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b* such that 0 < *b* − *a* < 2*π*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let *R* denote the region enclosed by a curve *r*(*φ*) and the rays *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b*, where 0 < *b* − *a* ≤ 2π.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] First, the interval [*a*, *b*] is divided into *n* subintervals, where *n* is some positive integer.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus Δ*φ*, the angle measure of each subinterval, is equal to *b* − *a* (the total angle measure of the interval), divided by *n*, the number of subintervals.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For each subinterval *i* = 1, 2, ..., *n*, let *φ**i* be the midpoint of the subinterval, and construct a sector with the center at the pole, radius *r*(*φ**i*), central angle Δ*φ* and arc length *r*(*φ**i*)Δ*φ*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] As the number of subintervals *n* is increased, the approximation of the area improves.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Taking *n* → ∞, the sum becomes the Riemann sum for the above integral.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using Cartesian coordinates, an infinitesimal area element can be calculated as *dA* = *dx* *dy*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Here, *R* is the same region as above, namely, the region enclosed by a curve *r*(*φ*) and the rays *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The formula for the area of *R* is retrieved by taking *f* identically equal to 1.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Vector calculus can also be applied to polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For a planar motion, let $\mathbf {r}$ be the position vector (*r* cos(*φ*), *r* sin(*φ*)), with *r* and *φ* depending on time *t*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] We define an orthonormal basis with three unit vectors: *radial, transverse, and normal directions*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term $r{\dot {\varphi }}^{2}$ is sometimes referred to as the *centripetal acceleration*, and the term $2{\dot {r}}{\dot {\varphi }}$ as the *Coriolis acceleration*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] These terms, which appear when acceleration is expressed in polar coordinates, are a mathematical consequence of differentiation; they appear whenever polar coordinates are used.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In planar particle dynamics, these accelerations appear when setting up Newton's second law of motion in a rotating frame of reference.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Here, these extra terms are often called fictitious forces; fictitious because they are simply a result of a change in coordinate frame.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] That does not mean they do not exist; rather, they exist only in the rotating frame.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Kinematic vectors in plane polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Notice the setup is not restricted to two-dimensional space, but a plane in any higher dimension.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For a particle in planar motion, one approach to attaching physical significance to these terms is based on the concept of an instantaneous **co-rotating frame of reference**.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] To define a co-rotating frame of reference, first an origin is selected from which the distance *r*(*t*) to the particle is defined.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] An axis of rotation is set up that is perpendicular to the plane of motion of the particle, and passing through this origin.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Then, at the selected moment *t*, the angular rate of the co-rotating frame Ω is made to match the rate of rotation of the particle about this axis, *dφ*/*dt*.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Next, the terms in the acceleration in the inertial frame are related to those in the co-rotating frame.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let the location of the particle in the inertial frame be (*r*(*t*), *φ*(*t*)), and in the co-rotating frame be denoted primed (*r*′(t), *φ*′(t)).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Because the co-rotating frame rotates at the same rate as the particle, *dφ*′/*dt* = 0.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The fictitious centrifugal force in the co-rotating frame is *mr*Ω2, radially outward.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The velocity of the particle in the co-rotating frame also is radially outward, because *dφ*′/*dt* = 0.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The *fictitious Coriolis force* therefore has a value −2*m*(*dr*/*dt*)Ω, pointed in the direction of increasing *φ* only.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus, using these forces in Newton's second law we find: $\mathbf {F} +\mathbf {F} _{\text{cf}}+\mathbf {F} _{\text{Cor}}=m{\ddot {\mathbf {r} }}\,,$ where over dots represent derivatives with respect to time, and **F** is the net real force (as opposed to the fictitious forces).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For general motion of a particle (as opposed to simple circular motion), the centrifugal and Coriolis forces in a particle's frame of reference commonly are referred to the instantaneous osculating circle of its motion, not to a fixed center of polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the modern terminology of differential geometry, polar coordinates provide coordinate charts for the differentiable manifold **R**2 \ {(0,0)}, the plane minus the origin.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Therefore, as expected, the punctured plane is a flat manifold.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar coordinate system is extended into three dimensions with two different coordinate systems, the cylindrical and spherical coordinate systems, both of which include two-dimensional or planar polar coordinates as a subset.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In essence, the cylindrical coordinate system extends polar coordinates by adding an additional distance coordinate, while the spherical system instead adds an additional angular coordinate.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The cylindrical coordinate system is a coordinate system that essentially extends the two-dimensional polar coordinate system by adding a third coordinate measuring the height of a point above the plane, similar to the way in which the Cartesian coordinate system is extended into three dimensions.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The third coordinate is denoted z , making the three cylindrical coordinates $(r,\theta ,z)$ .
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates can also be extended into three dimensions using the coordinates (ρ, φ, θ), where ρ is the distance from the pole, φ is the angle from the z-axis (called the colatitude or zenith and measured from 0 to 180°), and θ is the angle from the x-axis (as in the polar coordinates).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This coordinate system, called the spherical coordinate system, is similar to the latitude and longitude system used for Earth, with the latitude δ being the complement of φ, determined by δ = 90° − φ, and the longitude *l* being measured by *l* = θ − 180°.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are two-dimensional and thus they can be used only where point positions lie on a single two-dimensional plane.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] They are most appropriate in any context where the phenomenon being considered is inherently tied to direction and length from a center point.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For instance, the examples above show how elementary polar equations suffice to define curves—such as the Archimedean spiral—whose equation in the Cartesian coordinate system would be much more intricate.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Moreover, many physical systems—such as those concerned with bodies moving around a central point or with phenomena originating from a central point—are simpler and more intuitive to model using polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The initial motivation for the introduction of the polar system was the study of circular and orbital motion.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are used often in navigation as the destination or direction of travel can be given as an angle and distance from the object being considered.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For instance, aircraft use a slightly modified version of the polar coordinates for navigation.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In this system, the one generally used for any sort of navigation, the 0° ray is generally called heading 360, and the angles continue in a clockwise direction, rather than counterclockwise, as in the mathematical system.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Heading 360 corresponds to magnetic north, while headings 90, 180, and 270 correspond to magnetic east, south, and west, respectively.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus, an aircraft traveling 5 nautical miles due east will be traveling 5 units at heading 90 (read zero-niner-zero by air traffic control).
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Systems displaying radial symmetry provide natural settings for the polar coordinate system, with the central point acting as the pole.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A prime example of this usage is the groundwater flow equation when applied to radially symmetric wells.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Systems with a radial force are also good candidates for the use of the polar coordinate system.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] These systems include gravitational fields, which obey the inverse-square law, as well as systems with point sources, such as radio antennas.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Radially asymmetric systems may also be modeled with polar coordinates.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For example, a microphone's pickup pattern illustrates its proportional response to an incoming sound from a given direction, and these patterns can be represented as polar curves.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The curve for a standard cardioid microphone, the most common unidirectional microphone, can be represented as *r* = 0.5 + 0.5sin(*ϕ*) at its target design frequency.
[src:pie-donut-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The pattern shifts toward omnidirectionality at lower frequencies.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] A **radial tree**, or **radial map**, is a method of displaying a tree structure (e.g., a tree data structure) in a way that expands outwards, radially.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] It is one of many ways to visually display a tree, with examples dating back to the early 20th century.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] In use, it is a type of information graphic.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] The overall distance "d" is the distance between levels of the graph.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] It is chosen so that the overall layout will fit within a screen.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] Layouts are generated by working outward from the center, root.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] The first level is a special case because all the nodes have the same parent.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] The nodes for level 1 can be distributed evenly, or weighted depending on the number of children they have.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] For subsequent levels, the children are positioned within sectors of the remaining space, so that child nodes of one parent do not overlap with others.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] There are many extensions to this algorithm to create more visually balanced layouts, to allow users to navigate from node to node (changing the center), or accommodate node labels and combine force-directed layouts with radial layouts.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] The layout has some similarities to a hyperbolic tree, though a key difference is that hyperbolic trees are based on hyperbolic geometry, whereas in a radial tree the distance between orbits is relatively linear.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] In a simple case, the first node is at the top, and the linked nodes are beneath.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] As each node typically has more than one child, the resulting shape is relatively triangular.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] In a radial layout, instead of each successive generation being displayed a row below, each generation is displayed in a new, outer orbit.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] Since the length of each orbit increases with the radius, there tends to be more room for the nodes.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] A radial tree will spread the larger number of nodes over a larger area as the levels increase.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] We use the terms level and depth interchangeably.
[src:pie-donut-charts/radial-tree] Nevertheless, the number of nodes increases exponentially with the distance from the first node, whereas the circumference of each orbit increases linearly, so, by the outer orbits, the nodes tend to be packed together.
